PHOTO ESSAY / SUKKOT CELEBRATION / 2022-10-15
▫️
I photographed the last two days of Sukkot (Shemini Atzeret and Simchat Torah) in the Chabad-Lubavitch World Headquarters. 
Sukkot (Hebrew: סוכות‎ or סֻכּוֹת) commonly called the Feast of Tabernacles or in some translations the Festival of Shelters, and known also as the Feast of Ingathering, is a biblical Jewish holiday celebrate on the 15th day of the seventh month, Tishrei.  It’s celebrated for a week. It’s both an agricultural festival of thanksgiving and a commemoration of the forty-year period during which the Israelites wandered in the desert after leaving slavery in Egypt, living in temporary shelters as they traveled.

This was my first time in this synagogue.  Everyone was very friendly and I talked to a lot of people. This year was special and many people gathered from all over the world. I spoke with many people from different countries.  I did mention that I’m not Jewish and I don’t practice Judaism. There were few men that would always drag me dancing which was fun. 

I was invited to come back next day for Simchat Torah.  This day, there were probably ten times as many people and the service lasted for few hours.  You could barely breathe in the crowd and there were waves and waves of people coming in and leaving the building. I lasted for an hour and a half and it was tough to protect my camera.  Few times, I thought I was going to crack my ribs when I got in between those waves of people. But everyone was very friendly and very protective if people needed help.

The Chabad-Lubavitch World Headquarters is located on Eastern Parkway in the Crown Heights section of Brooklyn, New York, in the United States. The building is the center of the Chabad-Lubavitch world movement, and considered by many to be an iconic site in Judaism.

PHOTO ESSAY / FATIMA AL-ZAHRA PROCESSION / 2022-12-18
▫️
Fāṭima bint Muḥammad فَاطِمَة ٱبْنَت مُحَمَّد (605/15–632 CE), commonly known as Fāṭima al-Zahrāʾ (فَاطِمَة ٱلزَّهْرَاء), was the daughter of the Islamic prophet Muhammad and his wife Khadija. Fatima's husband was Ali, the fourth of the Rashidun Caliphs and the first Shia Imam. Fatima's sons were Hasan and Husayn, the second and third Shia Imams, respectively.  When Muhammad died in 632, Fatima and her husband Ali refused to acknowledge the authority of the first caliph, Abu Bakr. The couple and their supporters held that Ali was the rightful successor of Muhammad.  Fatima died in 11/632, within six months of Muhammad's death after a raid on her house.  She was buried secretly at night and her exact burial place remains uncertain.
▫️
The procession started around noon at the Big Bush Playground and finished at the Islamic Institute of New York. It lasted for several hours and the temperature was near or below freezing. There were several people serving warm chai and the chicken soup.  At the end, there was lots of delicious Pakistani food.

He is one of the people who cleans this mosque. Besides many interior spaces for prayer it has a large courtyard that’s paved with white marble pavers.  These men have to almost continuously clean it all day for people that come there for a prayer.
▫️
The Great Mosque of Herat مسجد جامع هرات‎ or Jami Masjid of Herat. It was built by the Ghurids, under the rule of the Sultan Ghiyath al-Din Muhammad Ghori, who laid its foundation in 1200 CE, and later extended by several rulers as Herat changed rulers down the centuries from the Timurids to the Safavids, Mughals and then the Uzbeks, all of whom supported the mosque. Though many of the glazed tiles have been replaced during subsequent periods, the Friday Mosque in Herat was given its present form during the closing years of the fifteenth century.

PHOTO ESSAY / THE 3RD ANNIVERSARY OF THE DOWNING OF FLIGHT PS752 / 2023-01-08
▫️
The protest was related to the 3rd anniversary of the downing of flight PS752 and in support of Iranian Revolution.  Ukraine International Airlines Flight 752 (PS752/AUI752) was a scheduled international civilian passenger flight from Tehran to Kyiv, operated by Ukraine International Airlines. On 8 January 2020, the Boeing 737-800 flying the route was shot down by the Islamic Revolutionary Guard Corps (IRGC) shortly after takeoff, killing all 176 passengers and crew aboard.  Missiles were fired at the aircraft by the IRGC amidst heightened tensions between Iran and the United States. The incident occurred five days after the United States carried out the assassination of Qasem Soleimani and some hours after Iran retaliated with Operation Martyr Soleimani.  Iranian authorities initially denied having any responsibility for the aircraft's destruction, but investigations by various intelligence agencies from the Western world as well as by the Iranian public later revealed that it had been struck by two surface-to-air missiles. On 11 January 2020, the Iranian government admitted that the IRGC had targeted Flight 752 after mistakenly identifying it as an American cruise missile.

▫️
Yesterday, I couldn’t attend the protest that was organised by the @wolpalestine, so I decided to post photos from the previous protest that I photographed last summer. I haven’t shared these photos in my previous posts.

It was organized in response to a murder of Shireen Abu Akleh who was a Palestinian-American reporter for the Al Jazeera for 25 years. She was reporting on an Israeli Defense Force (IDF) raid on a house in the Jerusalem and she was shot by the IDF.  Her funeral procession was brutally attacked by the IDF few days later.

The protest started around 1:00PM in Bay Ridge, Brooklyn.  There were many speakers from different organizations. The NYPD kept blocking and interrupting the procession. At some point, the procession was stopped for an hour.

Sukkot (Hebrew: סוכות‎ or סֻכּוֹת) commonly called the Feast of Tabernacles or in some translations the Festival of Shelters, and known also as the Feast of Ingathering, is a biblical Jewish holiday celebrate on the 15th day of the seventh month, Tishrei.  It’s celebrated for a week. It’s both an agricultural festival of thanksgiving and a commemoration of the forty-year period during which the Israelites wandered in the desert after leaving slavery in Egypt, living in temporary shelters as they traveled.

This was my first time in this synagogue.  Everyone was very friendly and I talked to a lot of people. This year was special and many people gathered from all over the world. I spoke with many people from different countries.  I did mention that I’m not Jewish and I don’t practice Judaism. There were few men that would always drag me dancing which was fun. 

I was invited to come back next day for Simchat Torah.  This day, there were probably ten times as many people and the service lasted for few hours.  You could barely breathe in the crowd and there were waves and waves of people coming in and leaving the building. I lasted for an hour and a half and it was tough to protect my camera.  Few times, I thought I was going to crack my ribs when I got in between those waves of people. But everyone was very friendly and very protective if people needed help.

The Chabad-Lubavitch World Headquarters is located on Eastern Parkway in the Crown Heights section of Brooklyn, New York, in the United States. The building is the center of the Chabad-Lubavitch world movement, and considered by many to be an iconic site in Judaism.

The West Indian Day Parade Carnival is an annual celebration of West Indian culture, held annually on around the first Monday of September in Crown Heights, Brooklyn, New York City. It is organized by the West Indian American Day Carnival Association (WIADCA).

The main event is the West Indian Day Parade (also known as simply the Labor Day Parade), which attracts between one and three million participants.  The spectators and participators watch and follow the parade on its route along Eastern Parkway. Some of the Caribbean islands represented in the parade include Trinidad and Tobago, Haiti, Barbados, Dominica, Saint Lucia, Jamaica, Saint Vincent and Grenada, along with some Afro-Panamanians. mainland Caribbean countries such as Guyana, Suriname, and Belize also participate as well.

Fāṭima bint Muḥammad فَاطِمَة ٱبْنَت مُحَمَّد (605/15–632 CE), commonly known as Fāṭima al-Zahrāʾ (فَاطِمَة ٱلزَّهْرَاء), was the daughter of the Islamic prophet Muhammad and his wife Khadija. She was buried secretly at night and her exact burial place remains uncertain.

One branch is typically placed above or below the others and its candle is used to light the other eight candles. This unique candle is called the shammash (שַׁמָּשׁ‎, "attendant"). Each night, one additional candle is lit by the shammash until all eight candles are lit together on the final night of the festival.
